der for all enterprises of the overriding importance of database backup ad recovery, and led many enterprises to adopt disaster recovery system, which is a non-disruptive recovery system. Although may not be the result of a terrorist attack as in the above example, failures frequently occur in the field, which cannot ensure transaction atomicity and durability due to various reasons such as hardware failure broken hard drive) , power outage, DBMS software defects, and s0 forth: Therefore, all database systems need a method of maintaining the atomicity ad persistence of transactions The recovery techniques used to restore a system to its previous state after the occurrence of a database failure (consistent state) should ensure high availability so that service downtime caused by the failure of the datahace canhe minimized during days ` they (e.g:','',2,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(823,'249','App\\Models\\Section','Text','Data recovery refers to the restoration f the consistency and integrity of a database before the occurrence of an unexpected (database) failure while operating the database','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(824,'250','App\\Models\\Section','Tables',NULL,'<Table 54  Types of database failures',1,'67b50a4269575.png','/storage/tables/67b50a4269575.png','2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:30'),(825,'418','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','and store a database to another storage device Copy','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(826,'419','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','al: Record the old values and new values of changing data each time a database is changed','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(827,'421','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','f the contents of the database itself are damaged, the most recent copy is loaded, and any changes made af making the copy are read the log and executed again so that the contents of the database can be restored: This corresponds to the completed transaction at the time of failure occurrence Changed values are stored in a disk (forward recovery) by executing the write operation from again','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(828,'422','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','If contents that are being changed or have been changed cannot be trusted even though the contents of the database itself have not been damaged, the database is restored to its original state by cancelling all changes This corresponds to the transaction in progress at the time of failure occurrence (incomplete transaction): Previous values are restored by cancelling the write operation (backward recovery):','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(829,'253','App\\Models\\Section','Tables',NULL,'<Table 55  Comparison of database recovery techniques',2,'67b50a427709b.png','/storage/tables/67b50a427709b.png','2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:30'),(830,'253','App\\Models\\Section','Figures',NULL,'[Figure 46] Types of database recovery techniques',1,'67b50a4281031.png','/storage/figures/67b50a4281031.png','2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:30'),(831,'423','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','This transaction accesses more than two databases, ad each DBMS can use different recovery techniques and transaction managers The atomicity of transactions is an important issue when building multiple database systems. If a certain transaction is executed across two sites and the transaction is not professionally designed, an inconsistent state can be caused when one site completes the transaction while the other site cancels the transaction The 2-phase commit protocol should be used to maintain the atomicity of multiple database transactions','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(832,'423','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Either all participating databases should complete the transaction, or none of them should complete it Even though a failure occurs in any participating database, recovery to the transaction completion state or cancellation state is possible.','',7,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(833,'424','App\\Models\\Subsection','Figures',NULL,'<Table 56  Execution of the 2-phase commit protocol',2,'67b50a4288d8c.png','/storage/figures/67b50a4288d8c.png','2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:30'),(834,'424','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','nis is the transaction completion protocol that is most widely used to maintain the atomicity of transactions in stributed database.','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(835,'424','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Step 1: When a transaction is started by transaction coordinator C, coordinator C sends a message whether the transaction can be completed to databases A and B, and database A and B reply with the \"ready\" status. 2: If all participating databases are \"ready\" , the coordinator sends a \"completion (commit)\" signal If one or more participating databases signals a \'not ready (abort)\" signal, the coordinator sends a \"cancellation (abort)\" signal. asking Step','',3,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(836,'425','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','The task of storing all or a part of a database in duplicate in order to recover the database in the event of a failure In general, the database is backed up every week, or month in units of incremental, differential, or full:. day,`','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(837,'426','App\\Models\\Subsection','Text','Prevent data loss: Recovers a database using duplicated data in the event of a failure. Secure business continuity: Minimizes business disruption caused by IT failure while processing business','',1,NULL,NULL,'2025-02-18 22:31:10','2025-02-18 22:31:10'),(838,'427','App\\Models\\Subsection','Tables',NULL,'<Table 57  Requirements by item',2,'67b50a42933fa.png','/storage/tables/67b50a42933fa.png','2025-02-18 22:31:10','2